It's not surprising that you admire Catholic philosophy of rights -- it is
based upon the absolute authority of a single individual, the pope.
Most of us who have democratic leanings have relegated this Aristotlean
philosophy to the dustbin of history.



: In defense, intelligence, criminal, and certain economic matters the
: government has an absolute right under the common defense and domestic
: tranquility provisions to keep things secret if revealing them would lead to
: unacceptable consequences. "The People" don't have any right to war plans in

This is false. If moral 'rights' can only be granted by a bureaucracy
(whether elected or not) then roman slaves had no 'right' to be free
nor did women have any 'right' to vote.  Since this is absurd, Sternlight's
view of rights is defective.

